  "footnotes": [
    "Great Moravia (833–907): the first major West Slavic state, centered in modern Moravia and western Slovakia; Prince Rastislav invited Saints Cyril and Methodius from Byzantium in 863, who created the Glagolitic script and translated liturgical texts into Old Church Slavonic; the state collapsed under Magyar invasions after 895",
    "Přemyslid dynasty (c.870–1306): the founding dynasty of the Czech state ruled for over four centuries; under Ottokar II (1253–1278) Bohemia briefly controlled Austria, Styria, Carinthia, and Carniola, making it one of the most powerful states in Europe before his defeat by Rudolf of Habsburg",
    "Charles IV and the Golden Age (1346–1378): as both King of Bohemia and Holy Roman Emperor, Charles made Prague an imperial capital; he founded Charles University (1348), built the Charles Bridge, and the Golden Bull of 1356 confirmed Bohemia's electoral status; Prague was the third-largest city in Europe",
    "Hussite Wars (1419–1434): following Jan Hus's execution, Bohemia erupted in Europe's first major proto-Protestant revolution; the Hussite armies under Jan Žižka defeated five consecutive crusades; the movement prefigured the Reformation by a century and established Czech religious distinctiveness",
    "Battle of White Mountain (1620): the decisive Habsburg victory ended Bohemian independence for 300 years; 27 Czech Protestant leaders were executed in Old Town Square; forced re-Catholicization and Germanization followed; the Czech language nearly disappeared from public life until the National Revival",
    "Munich Agreement (1938): Britain and France allowed Nazi Germany to annex the Sudetenland (German-speaking border regions); Czechoslovakia lost its fortifications and 30% of its territory without being consulted; Hitler occupied the rest in March 1939 — the word 'Munich' became synonymous with appeasement",
    "Prague Spring (1968): Alexander Dubček's reform program of 'socialism with a human face' was crushed by Warsaw Pact invasion on 21 August 1968; the trauma deepened Czech-Slovak divisions and fueled the dissident movement (Charter 77) that ultimately led to the Velvet Revolution of 1989"
  ]
